reviews.text: At first I was a little put off by the need to have a reservation at a cafe for breakfast.  Then WOW now I understand.  The atmosphere is a mix between industrial and boho.  The staff is friendly and fast.  The food is outstanding.

Portage Bay is a chain of cafes in Seattle, the one in U District is pretty solid. The quality of the food is clearly very high, there menu ranges from sandwiches to breakfast stables to seasonal dishes like crepes and such. I personally have been here around 3 times, the environment is very very busy on the weekends, however the service is fast and attentive to whatever your needs are. I dont have a photo of it, but they have a toppings bar with some of the best whipped cream I've had - it also has a plethora of fresh berries. Overall great spot for brunch with the parents, I would recommend getting a reservation before you go for sure.

Was looking to catch up with some of my best girl friends over a girly brunch and stumbled upon Portage Bay in the University District. I seriously did not realize how popular this place was--but wow, I get the hype.

First tip: MAKE A RESERVATION ON OPENTABLE. I was lucky enough to snag one (bless), and even with a reservation, we waited around 15 minutes to be seated. It was a Sunday brunch, so we expected a bit of chaos, but it still felt overwhelming. There was a line out the door with people waiting outside, the level of noise in the space is quite loud. While waiting for our table or even seated at our table, it was a bit hard to hear one another. This is not the space for a quiet girly brunch for sure. That said--would say the food is 100% worth it.

Don't come hungry or hangry as it did take close to an hour for our food to arrive (yes, we were HANGRY), but when it did, the first ten minutes was silence of devouring our meal. Service was okay, the servers seem uninterested to be there, barely checked in - we had to ask about status of our food and get his attention.

We ordered the Smoked Salmon Benedict, Seattle Benedict (with Dungeness crab!), 2 Rancher Breakfasts (3 eggs your way, house potatoes, one with chicken sausage + pancake, the other with bacon + French toast). Honestly such a cute idea to do a berry bar, the menu lists items that gives you access to a literal berry buffet--fresh berries, whipped cream, butter...

The benedicts were the best menu choice--rich, flavorful, and perfectly portioned. The Rancher Breakfasts were huge and hearty--perfect for anyone rolling in with major hunger. The chicken sausage was flavorful and the potatoes were crispy on the outside, soft on the inside.

I am a BIG pancake girly, and their pancakes were giant, fluffy, with the perfect hint of sweetness. I ate my entire meal plus one pancake and still had leftovers for dinner and breakfast the next day. No regrets.

The coffee here is just okay. Seattle has no shortage of amazing coffee shops, would recommend saving your caffeine intake for one of those instead--which we did, shoutout Ugly Mug Coffee, which was the move.

We came in as a pretty large group with a reservation (which I recommend given how long the lines were when we arrived) and were seated in about 15 minutes after arriving.

The food and menu options are really good! There are quite a few vegetarian options (especially if you‚Äôre open to eggs). I ordered the migas which was incredibly flavorful and massive! I also got a side of pancakes and loaded up on fruits and nuts at the breakfast bar! I can‚Äôt wait to go back and try other things on the menu!

I want to start this off by saying my review does not reflect in any way the staff or their behavior. All the staff I interacted with were wonderful.
I was really disappointed by my experience here. I'm a HUGE eggs Benedict fan and I have consistently been recommended this establishment for their renditions of this dish. I made a reservation, and though I got to the restaurant on time, I was told I would need to wait an extra fifteen minutes due to the restaurant being busy (to be fair, it was very busy. But then what was the point of my reservation which I made weeks in advance?). A positive was when we did get seated, our food came out rather quickly. And I want to say I liked it, but I was thoroughly disappointed with my Benedict. I felt their English muffin was heavy and biscuit-y in texture, but by far the worst was that both of my poached eggs had hard yolks (not by my request). The carnitas were a mix of some perfect bites, and some incredibly dry ones. I would say that I was disappointed by the quality of my meal, considering the reviews I've gotten previously.
Once again, the staff were excellent people, and they sure know how to handle business! I just wish my experience could have been better.

reviews.text:
Rick helped us plan an amazing fundraising event for our university organization! It was a great turnout and so much fun. The beer was amazing and the food was great! I got the verde nachos which were a massive portion for a great price.
As a self proclaimed beer snob the dark beers (porter and oatmeal stout) were so smooth and absolutely delicious.
I plan on returning often and supporting Rick and his brewery and you should too!

Had the pork verde nachos here along with a couple of beers. These nachos came in a massive plate - the portion size was a bit excessive to be honest.
There was a ton of cheese - comprising the vast majority of the toppings on the chips. The pork was probably the second-most present, followed by jalapenos

The cheese was probably the only decent thing here. It really was melted well onto the chips, and I got a pretty good cheese pull with each bite.
However, the rest of it was not great. I did not like the pork - as it felt pretty dry, and without its juiciness lost most of its flavor. The chips themselves were fine - a little bit stale but decently crunchy.

What was truly terrible was the salsa verde. This just tasted like water that looked green. I don't know what was in this but it might've been the worst salsa I've ever had.

Overall, I like most things about this brewery, but ordering the nachos will have you regretting your decision less-than-halfway through. 4/10

Went to Big Time Brewery last night, as it was the only thing open around 10pm toward the bottom of The Ave. We were going to go to Cafe on The Ave for a coffee and a bite to eat, since usually they‚Äôre open late. However they were closed.

We deliberated for a bit before going in, but ultimately decided to give it a chance.

We noticed that we needed to order at the bar, so we walked back to where a very pleasant gal greeted us. She had a great smile and warm welcoming vibe, which sold me on the place :) She patiently waited while we went over menu options. They have a very extensive menu, so it took us some time.  One of us is a strict vegan, and thankfully they had some great options available for her :) We finally landed on the vegan pizza, which she brought over to our table up front near the window, she even brought us cutlery and napkins which was just an extra level of  service that I personally really appreciated!

The atmosphere was super chill not crazy busy or packed, which was nice, so we could do what we set out to do there in the first place, which was to discuss our weekly night Metal Mondayze up at Innervisions. I took over the iconic poster shop, along with Ken Tomkins from Seattle Records.

We didn‚Äôt have a whole lot of time to spend, but we sure were able to maximize it due to the friendly service, and being able to hold a conversation without a bunch of distractions.

I would highly recommend
BIG Time Brewery!

I even noticed when I‚Äôd walked by before, people were even playing Chess! That‚Äôs an added bonus and another reason to return, as Ken who I mentioned before, owns Seattle Records and just happens to be a chess grandmaster :)

Thanks again for having the absolute gem of a business going at the bottom of The Ave!

The employees are equally impressive ‚Äî polite, professional, and always welcoming. Their kind behavior and respectful attitude create a warm and comfortable atmosphere for every customer.

No other restaurant can compare to Aladdin Gyros when it comes to both taste and service. Highly recommended!

The Aladdin fries got me through college, big time. They are by far the biggest serving and most affordable food spot on The Ave. They are sooo delicious, and every time I am in the area -- it is a requirement that I order some. My friend is also a big fan of their chicken shawarma!

They are open late, and staff is always so kind. There is seating inside, but I typically order take-out. They can get busy during the later hours, so please be patient -- I promise it is worth it. Highly recommend!

Twas 2 hours past nightfall, we entered the restaurant hopes high as the sky, intimidated by the long line but alas we made it through. Our number was 67 so naturally it was a W overall delish food and fun vibes, slightly spicy.

editorial_summary.overview: Casual, cozy downstairs restaurant serving classic Thai dishes with a focus on seafood & vegetables.

formatted_address: 4142 Brooklyn Ave NE #105, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Little Thai Restaurant

reviews.text: I love this hidden gem in the U-District. Tucked away downstairs this unassuming Thai restaurant serves delicious Thai staples and dishes in a relaxed and laid back environment. The food is always served quickly and piping hot making it an ideal place to get lunch. My favorite dish is the Jungle Curry which is flavorful, healthy, and filling. The options of protein to add to your curry is also a great option depending on diet and preference.

I headed to the U District to have lunch with my son at a little thai restaurant in the district, which was appropriately named ‚ÄúLittle Thai Restaurant.‚Äù Haha. The small restaurant was packed and very loud, but it had a positive vibe. We ordered Massaman Curry with tofu and Pad Thai with tofu. Both dishes were good. The service was great!

The service and atmosphere were fine. You have to flag down a server whenever you need anything instead of them coming to check on you much, which is fine but can be difficult if they‚Äôre busy with many tables. All the staff members were polite and helpful.  However, our food was sub-par and disappointing. We ordered the drunken noodles and Panang curry, both hot, as well as the papaya salad and two sides of rice. Neither main dish was spicy at all but the papaya salad was, which was nice at least.

The drunken noodles were hammered while cooking to the point where the ‚Äúnoodles‚Äù were mushy and falling apart into goo. The curry was okay. All the vegetables felt undercooked in both meals. Both tasted extremely one note ‚Äî mostly something like soy sauce for the drunken noodles. We are on vacation and felt like this was a wasted dining out opportunity. Super disappointing.

We were in the area and planned to come to this place for dinner. In order to use the restroom, you have to use one of their passes which has a key on it. The restrooms were a little dirty and not well-maintained as evidenced by the lack of soap and paper towels, however, I was grateful for the chance to use the facilities. I got the phad see ew with fried tofu, and my partner got the Thai pulled pork. Our server was Pete, but someone else came by to take our order and bring our food out. The phad see eq was delicious. I do not usually get tofu with this dish, but I decided to try something different. The tofu went really well with the noodles, egg, cabbage, and broccoli. The Thai pulled pork was absolutely delicious! It came with some sort of dipping sauce that was equally delicious. We had a really nice meal here, and our dishes both were under $15 which made it a reasonably-priced dinner. They also have some fish tanks which looked well-maintained and very nice. I highly recommend this place!

Very affordable Thai food, especially for the area, but unfortunately I‚Äôm not a huge fan of their food. I know a lot of folks who are tho so maybe it‚Äôs just me. Got the Tom Yum soup here once and the chicken Jungle Curry another time and wasn‚Äôt a fan of either. I think I liked the red curry more. The Jungle curry tasted a lot like fish sauce and the chicken lacked flavor.

editorial_summary.overview: Part of local ramen chain with many options & noodles made in-house, served in a no-frills setting.

formatted_address: 4138 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Samurai Noodle

reviews.text:
This is a place where you go in, pick a spot, then you're waited on, pay at the counter.

I was in the mood for some spicy ramen and the spicy shoyu tonkotsu ramen hit the spot that day. I was given water, but no refills, not great when you get a spicy dish.

However, the value isn't there, especially if you get the karaage, $8 for four medium size pieces of chicken. For ramen, a side, and tip, it was $33, one of my most expensive lunches in the U district.

First issue was probably ordering this as a delivery order. Noodles are always better fresh.
BUT they did a great job packaging. The kaarage was really nice crispy. Loved the chili sauce it came with. The takoyaki was a little too soft for me, but it was due to steam from the package. The noodle type was not my favorite but I am glad I gave it try to know now. I loved the soft boiled egg. I think this would be a better place to go into and enjoy for sure.
I did appreciate the different options for soup bases. Give it a go but in person.

A great staple at the u district they have daily specials with great value.  Can‚Äôt go wrong with anything in this restaurant the food is great, service is quick and it‚Äôs affordable.  Highly recommended.  My favorite is the samurai bowl try it

I liked this spot fairly well. One thing that I will say was the noodles were a little thin for my liking. However the broth definitely makes up for it. I got the tonkatsu ramen and the broth was so creamy and the taste was so phenomenal. The service was solid as well as the atmosphere. We went during a super nice and quiet time of the day where it felt super calm within the building. Overall would definitely recommend coming here.

Well priced, tasty, and great service. Will come again!
Great vegan options too!
Cheap sake that tastes good üòå
Make sure you have enough friends if you commit to a bottle!

editorial_summary.overview: Late-night counter-service spot serving shawarma, kebabs, gyros & falafel.

formatted_address: 4337 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Shawarma King

reviews.text:
Overall very good. Been here more than 10 times.

This is probably the best shawarma in U-district and I might even say Seattle. The meat is very high quality and the flavor is so good it doesn‚Äôt need to be drenched is sauce. The garlic sauce is amazing with the fries that I needed another. The service is great and welcoming. The staff is the best and I even befriended Mohamed who was very nice. 10/10
The food is always hot and fresh. The best place for consistent, quality, food with a great staff who treats you like family. Everytime.

Food is always great, very delicious/ clean great environment.

Mohammad is a very great individual, beyond great personality. Very nice gentleman.

Thank you Mohammad

editorial_summary.overview: Quick-serve Korean eatery is a casual, college-town go-to for bibimbop, soups & BBQ.

formatted_address: 4142 Brooklyn Ave NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Korean Tofu House

reviews.text: Cute spot with tasty Korean food. I tried it a month ago and came back again. The ox bone soup was flavorful, garlicky, and delicious. Portions are generous, and the side dishes are great. Small space and usually crowded during peak hours. Metered parking available nearby.

I have been to this Korean restaurant in the University district for several years but today was my first time going there for dinner. Overall it was good. I loved the bibimbap and seafood pancake! My friend ordered the japche and he couldn‚Äôt eat it because it was too sweet. Lastly, it was so hot in the restaurant with no AC that it was hard to really enjoy our food. So we didn‚Äôt stay long and took our food to go.
This food was so fulfilling. I order the beef buldogi and it was definitely worth my money!üíµ Would order again, and the environment was very welcoming.
Food was delicious. We only eat halal and they were very accommodating with non-meat options. I recommend the seafood pancake, the japchae, and the Tteok-bokki. They also have amazing side dishes.

This is by far the best Korean restaurant in the city. I would compare it to Moodoo up north. The BBQ beef is my favorite and the Kimchi pancakes are incredible (although I must say Moodoo‚Äôs is better). Chicken with cheese was a little dry to my liking. Soondubu is great according to my gf although I have never been a fan of it. Toppoki and Japchae are other dishes I like. I go back there every time and always get the BBQ beef - highly recommended!

editorial_summary.overview: Made-to-order Vietnamese meals, from sandwiches to rice bowls, in a modern counter-serve setup.

formatted_address: 1313 NE 42nd St, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Sizzle&Crunch Vietnamese Grill

reviews.text:
Overall, really solid price‚Äìquality‚Äìquantity balance.
I ordered the grilled beef bowl with all the toppings, plus the green sauce and their soy sauce‚Äîand I loved it. The meat was juicy and definitely grilled‚Äînot boiled or bland. It had that slightly smoky flavor.
The soy sauce wasn‚Äôt just plain soy‚Äîit had a sweet and spicy twist that added a lot of flavor. The toppings were fresh and crunchy, and the green sauce was fantastic too‚Äîbright and flavorful without overpowering the rest of the bowl.
One of my favorite place at the UDistrict my favorite is the chicken bowl and that green sauce is to die for also don‚Äôt forget the egg on top of rice delicious

As a Vietnamese person, this is possibly the worst banh mi I've ever had. The bread, which is essential to the identity of this kind of sandwich, is entirely wrong. It's like a hoagie roll and was dry. I had their banh mi at the SLU location last year and that bread wasn't great either but this is on another level. There are Vietnamese bakeries and delis that make Vietnamese baguettes in Seattle that can supply so this is not excusable imo. Other Vietnamese restaurants can get the right bread, why not here. As for the fillings, it's ok. Ingredients are fresh. Not the most flavorful chicken but I did appreciate that there was plenty of meat and veggies.
I also had a rice bowl here, reminiscent of com tam. Rice bowl was much better, though fish sauce was just ok.
Workers were kind and speedy but interaction was minimal.
At the end of the day, it's like chipotle to Mexican food. It's not authentic really (they asked if I wanted fish sauce with the sandwich which was odd‚Äînever encountered that before in America or Vietnam) but it works I guess. I'm not gonna come back when there's other smaller Viet restaurants in the u-district I can support UNLESS the bread situation improves.

I‚Äôm not a picky person, but the bahn mi was literally barely cut and they just threw everything onto it and it could not even shut  because it was not properly cut. I ordered two and they were both like this. We literally could not eat it. Any other bahn mi place around is good this place was terrible

Ive been coming here for 6 years now and every single time it hits. My favorite order is the housepork plate, it‚Äôs just the go to. I usually substitute one of the meats in the plate to Tofu because their braised tofu is absolutely banger! They give extra sauces on the side but that green sauce is üíï. Sadly this place has very limited seating but don‚Äôt worry the food tastes good even after a drive home or to a park!

editorial_summary.overview: UW campus dining option, also open to the public, features social spaces & 5 restaurants.

formatted_address: 1245 NE Campus Pkwy, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Local Point

reviews.text: Food are edible. Every once in a while, there will be bug in your food, and it will just be a tale to laugh about it. Service is usally bad. The atmosphere is very factory-like. People in HFS need to get paid more to probably think about doing more. A lot of renovation should be made to the place; it nees light and cleaniness. A stricter management need to be enforce for the consistency and quality of food provided here.
Sandwich was not bad. The location was good.
I think the food here is solid. It has a lot of variety and free drinks. It gets a bit busy during the lunch and dinner hours, but if you go in early or late you get your food relatively quickly
This was just air and breading. 12$?? Hell naw
This dish had so much oil the us government is about to invade the damn plate. Tastes terrible and was 14 for a scoop of rice and chicken. More oil then actual food.

editorial_summary.overview: Snug, no-frills eatery & deli offering southern Indian fare headlined by its lineup of dosas.

formatted_address: 4220 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Chili's South Indian Cuisine

reviews.text:
I recently ordered from Chili‚Äôs South Indian Cuisine on November 11th at around 2 PM, and my experience was overall very positive. The food was tasty, fresh, and full of authentic flavor. Everything was packed neatly, and the service was fast

The prices are very reasonable for the quality and generous portions. I especially enjoyed the Poori with Potato Masala and the Masala Dosa, both were cooked perfectly and flavorful. The restaurant clearly takes care to maintain quality and consistency.

The only downside was that parking was a bit challenging to find, which made picking up the order slightly stressful. However, once parked, everything went smoothly, and the staff was friendly and helpful.

Overall, Chili‚Äôs is a reliable spot for quick, flavorful South Indian food. Despite the minor inconvenience with parking, I‚Äôll definitely be ordering again and would recommend it to anyone looking for fresh, well-prepared Indian cuisine.

When we entered the restaurant, it looked great and had a quiet, pleasant atmosphere. The food was okay ‚Äî not extraordinary, just average. However, our experience ended on a very uncomfortable note. Before leaving, we spoke with a lady at the counter and paid our bill. But as we were walking out, our server ‚Äî a young lady ‚Äî stopped us in front of many other customers and asked if we had paid. It was embarrassing and made us feel very awkward. This situation could have been handled more politely and professionally. A quick check before approaching us like that would have been much more respectful.

Option 1 (friendly & casual):
Authentic Indian flavors, great service, and a warm atmosphere! Perfect spot for group chats and enjoying delicious food together.

Visited for dinner and ordered the veg thali and puttu with fish curry. The veg thali was bland ‚Äî curries lacked flavor, sambhar was missing, and the dessert was overwhelmed by cinnamon. Puttu with fish curry was just okay, could use more punch. Buttermilk was the only highlight. Spent $54 ‚Äî not worth the price.

When I shared my feedback, the person I believe to be the owner seemed quite defensive ‚Äî she cut the conversation short after just one point, without taking in the full feedback.

Stunningly sub-par dosas. I have had dosas across the globe and this one, am sorry to say, qualifies as the worst dosas I have ever had. It didn't even feel like it was fermented. Thick and pudg and flaccid. I ordered the one with ghee/butter -+ I could neither taste nor smell either. Butter is the cheapest thing you can get -- be a bit more generous.

I would strongly suggest that the chef/establishment should try a little harder. It's not rocket science to make half-decent dosas.

The only high point was the server -- the kind, Latino gentleman who served me was polite and courteous. That's what the extra star is for.

editorial_summary.overview: Pho, banh mi & other Vietnamese staples in a simple storefront with a neon-accented dining room.

formatted_address: 4235 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Pho Shizzle

reviews.text: 10/10 every single time. Portions are good. Kitchen prep must be really prepared because your food will come out in under 5 minutes. Service is quick!

I had a pleasant stop here after visiting the University of Washington. It was a truly lovely sight, and this restaurant offered very good food from a wide range available on this street. I would definitely stop by again during my next vacation.

Never have I gotten food faster. I was meeting with friends here and they already got their food so as soon as I arrived I sat down and they immediately asked me what I wanted. I ordered and got it not even 5 minutes later, it was very quick service and I have no complaints at all. Will be coming back soon.

They may have taken the cleanliness comments from previous reviews too close to heart - pho and hainan chicken were fine, but tasted vaguely off‚Ä¶ like all the bowls and silverware still had a layer of soap on it. Overall cleanliness of interior and service was fine, nothing nearly as bad as some of the reviews might claim.
pho is solid but the grilled vermicelli bowls are the best and really good value.

editorial_summary.overview: Mediterranean eatery serving falafel & gyros in a cheery green space with colorful wall murals.

formatted_address: 1319 NE 43rd St, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Cedars of Lebanon

reviews.text: This family restaurant named for the iconic (and sadly endangered) Lebanese Cedar Tree has been a staple of Seattle since 1974 and the U-District since 1976. Over the past 50 years it has been serving delicious Lebanese food in one of the most collective international foodie locations in the City of Seattle! It's steadfast history will be made all the more obvious when you taste the delicious  cuisine of the Eastern Mediterranean. I had the Shawarma Plate with a Turkish Coffee and my partner had the Shish Kebob Enree. Both were served with generous portions, were packed full of excellent spice flavours, and came over rice, a side of delicious fattoush salad, and pita bread. The service was fast and one of the friendliest I have had in my past seven years of living in Seattle. They also have a take out window and outdoor seating. I highly recommend and will be back soon with friends. ‚ù§Ô∏èüá±üáß‚ù§Ô∏è

Based on preliminary research, Cedars of Lebanon, which was established in 1974, is the only restaurant still open from when I went to school at UW in the mid-1980s. I don‚Äôt recall visiting there when I was a student so I decided to go there for lunch. It is a cramped restaurant with beautiful murals on the wall and supplies stored in booths. I ordered the Gyros Plate, which I thought was the famous sandwich of lamb, veggies, wrapped in pita bread. However, the ‚Äúplate‚Äù is lamb, veggies, rice, and pita bread on the side‚Ä¶kind of a deconstructed Gyro sandwich. I happily ate my meal while reconstructing mini gyros. It was good and the service was great!

Open for over 50 years.

At the spry age of 75, John still looks like he can hit a home run.

And he'd probably let you hear it too.

In 2025, Cedars of Lebanon can only be described as a fixture of University District. My first time here, and I've already caught conversations with customers who have been coming by for 3 decades.

We ordered falafel wraps, foul mudammas, and greek fries. Real ingredients made with hands wrinkled from a lifetime.

Though from his smiles, prayers, and words of love - you'd think John is only getting started.

"I wish you two a happy life", he says as we got up.

See you next time.

I stopped here to break up my commute home. I'm a big fan of Greek gyros and was interested to taste the Lebonese version. The interior decor is...let's say it has a hole-in-the-wall charm to it. This place is set-up for takeaway orders through the window that faces the street; so I can appreciate the interior being a lower priority. The staff is kind and prompt. The gyros were delicious with a healthy portion of meat and just the right amount of sauce. The pricing is better than the Greek restaurant near my building where they charge two dollars more per gyro. I'll definitely eat here again.

The owner is incredibly humorous and friendly! When I asked if they accepted Apple Pay, he joked and said, ‚ÄúSure, we take Mango Pay üòÇ.‚Äù The food was absolutely delicious, and the prices were very affordable. Highly recommend!

editorial_summary.overview: Coffeehouse with a big American menu of breakfast staples & sandwiches in comfy digs with free WiFi.

formatted_address: 4201 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Cafe on the Ave

reviews.text: The kimchi fried rice here is seriously delicious. In a way, I think it could be considered this place‚Äôs signature dish. I also ordered an Americano, and it wasn‚Äôt too bitter at all‚Äîit was just right for my taste. The staff overall were really friendly, and it feels like they pay good attention to keeping the place clean. As expected! I‚Äôll definitely be coming back here again.!

Friendly staff. Standard college town breakfast: big portions. Appreciated the ability to sit there with my dog. The chicken on the chicken and waffle tasted like bigger versions of the popcorn chicken sold in boba cafes. Omelette was huge. Wasn't too crowded when we went for lunch on a weekday.

This is a counter service place, order and take a number to your table, they bring the food, self bus.

The menu is surprisingly large for a place that calls its self a cafe, there's some options that you wouldn't expect like bibimbap and katsudon.

I got the Ave Club, it's not a normal club sandwich but I still enjoyed it. It's a big sandwich too, was plenty to fill me up fo lunch.

I had also gotten an Americano, while reasonably priced, it was pretty average, you can find a better coffee elsewhere in the area.

Great place to eat, drink and talk with friends in UW!!!
The food we ordered came out really quickly and was plentiful.
The crispy pork cutlet, burger, and pasta were really delicious.
Next time, I definitely want to try the signature dish, kimchi fried rice.

I used to really like this caf√© (and recommend to my friends), but lately their quality has dropped. In the past month alone, I‚Äôve had three separate instances where I didn‚Äôt receive the coffee I ordered. A caramel macchiato is supposed to be sweet, but mine only tasted sweet for the first few sips; after that, the remaining three-quarters tasted like plain coffee. I‚Äôm not paying $5 for something I can get for free at the university.

On top of that, the staff doesn‚Äôt seem to know the menu well. As a coffee enthusiast, I asked for a specific espresso combination to make the drink sweeter, yet they still served me plain coffee for $5, again. This has happened three times now. After a few sips, I end up throwing the drink away right outside the shop.

Unless the staff gets proper training about the menu and coffees and improves their communication, I‚Äôll be taking my business to other caf√©s (and recommending my friends to do the same).

editorial_summary.overview: Late-night standby serves up burgers, kebabs & other global grub at the counter in unfussy environs.

formatted_address: 4142 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Burger Hut

reviews.text:
Burger Hut in the University District near UW is a true gem for anyone craving something satisfying after a long day‚Äîor a wild night out. Their paneer and veggie burgers are the real stars of the menu: simple, fresh, and downright delicious. The paneer  is flavorful and perfectly seasoned, while the veggie burger strikes that balance of slight crunch, hearty goodness that makes you wonder why you ever needed meat in the first place. The menu isn‚Äôt overly complicated, and that‚Äôs exactly what makes it great‚Äîjust good food done right.

What truly sets Burger Hut apart is its late-night availability and relaxed vibe. Whether you‚Äôre wrapping up a study session or stumbling out from a party in the U-District, this place becomes the go-to spot to satisfy both your hunger and your mood. It‚Äôs one of those places where every bite feels comforting, where the food hits just right at 1 a.m., and where a simple burger can make your night feel complete. Tasty, accessible, and always reliable‚ÄîBurger Hut keeps winning hearts, one late-night bite at a time. They have branches in Bellevue and soon To be opened in Bothell.

I ordered a meal to go and halfway through watching them cook I had to leave. I watched the cook pulling beef patties out of a box that was on the ground, no gloves being used and the cook was pulling earwax out of his ear while at the grill. Not a care in the world.
The total lack of hygiene was astounding.
I paid for my food when I ordered and didn‚Äôt even ask for my money back, I just left.
I highly recommend not eating at this establishment if you care about sanitation.

I really like the Paneer burger here. They give you a big piece of marinated paneer, that has been cooked on the griddle, the seasoning is on point. Just delicious. They have also done renovations. The service is good too. It's a perfect spot to grab something tasty, quickly on the go.

I ate here for the first time today. I went around 12:30pm, and was the only customer. My burger was made to order, as were the fries. The young man at the counter was friendly enough, but I think a language barrier had him a bit slow on understanding my order. That was fine, he was earnestly trying.
The good: my burger tasted pretty good! The fries were nice and hot! The lettuce was kinda brown and wilty. But the slice of tomato seemed good and the burger was cooked medium-well, which is my preference.
The bad: Folks, this place is not clean. From the front door to the peek behind the curtain into the kitchen, to the all-gender bathroom, it looks like they view ‚Äúcleaning‚Äù to be a quick wipe with a damp towel - at best.
The front door is grimy and the window needs to be cleaned. There‚Äôs a thin film of yuk on the tables. And guys, come on, the bathroom had a bottle of spray cleaner sitting on the toilet tank with two meager napkins, but neither the toilet nor the sink had been wiped down in some time. There was no handsoap, no hand towels, and the air dryer was not working. That‚Äôs just gross.
The whole place needs a deep cleaning.
Now, I love me some greasy diner type joints as much as the next guy. And your burger was pretty good. Show some pride. Clean up the place.
I will return here in spite of my detracting comments. If it‚Äôs clean and the food is still good, I will be a recurring customer. If not, I won‚Äôt be back.

UPDATE: I went today (10/22) months after my first visit. I‚Äôm conflicted.
On one hand the guy who wrote down my order and cooked it got it very wrong. However, to his enormous credit, when he noticed it, he volunteered a genuine apology. And I told him thanks, I really appreciated it, but I will eat it anyway. I had already started eating, and the thing is, the burger tasted good. The fries were very hot. The guy is busting his tail, making everything one order at a time. It‚Äôs a burger, and this ain‚Äôt Canlis. The day I go full Karen over a wrong order is the day my villain origin story begins. Ain‚Äôt happening.

The flip side is nothing is any more clean than my first visit. This time I took a photo of the bathroom situation. Now the paltry paper towels are sitting on an extra roll of TP. There‚Äôs still no paper towels to dry hands on. The tables are grimy.

Bottom line: the food tasted good, the guy is working really hard, and I respect the heck out of him. But I recommend you take your order to go, because sitting in there to eat is gross.

Geeked review pilot - E01

Arrived at 1:05. Ordered eggplant burger medium spicy fries and coke zero. Guy who took my order was very polite. Nice amount of seating. Service a little slow, got food around 120, but I didn't really mind because I got to check up on stuff for classes tomorrow.

I wasn't sure what to exactly expect with the eggplant burger but I've been looking to get more into eggplant lately so I thought I'd explore a potential use case. Burger came on a sesame seed bun with roasted eggplant, cheese, mayo, ketchup, lettuce, tomato, pickles, and some sort of chili sauce akin to sambal olek. The burger was delicious. The fries were good and I could imagine them being even better with some sort of garlicky sauce rather than ketchup. They had some sort of masala and paired well with the burger.

I'd like to return and potentially check out the paneer masala burger, and maybe a different fry option. Overall very good spot and will be back.

editorial_summary.overview: Colorful breakfast & lunch cafe set in a hotel featuring American eats with coffee, beer & wine.

formatted_address: 4242 Roosevelt Way NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Pineapple Caf√©

reviews.text: Despite being named the Pineapple Cafe I was disappointed to find a lack of pineapple options. I am not sure why all the bad reviews. I got my white chocolate mocha and sandwich in the morning. Both were tasty! The White Chocolate Mocha latte had to be some of the best coffee I ever had and I have been to Vietnam, and Costa Rica.

The barista, Joanna I think her name was, was so kind and thoughtful and had overall wonderful customer service. We had a great conversation as she prepared my order. I ordered a latte and a bagel. My food came quickly and the latte was delicious! Overall great experience. I will be back

The tall guy barista will make it seem like it‚Äôs something wrong with you being in a coffee shop as a black man. Your experience here will be one of passive racism and deep discomfort which is unfortunate because the other staff are cool. I‚Äôve tried several times thinking it was a one off but no matter what I was made to feel like I was committing a crime just for ordering coffee please just put the sign up NO BLACKS ALLOWED!

Went there to pick up breakfast to go at 7:30 am before a meeting. They were out of stock on nearly every breakfast item. They had no breakfast sandwiches, no breakfast burritos, and didn‚Äôt even have cream cheese for their bagels. This is poor planning for the hotel breakfast option.

formatted_address: 1312 NE 43rd St, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Kai's Thai Street Food And Bar

reviews.text: We visited Kai's Thai in Seattle in the U district and were not disappointed. There are so many choices of food in this area that it was difficult to decide where to eat. Im so glad this is what we chose. The service is amazing and the food is spectacular. We started with crab puffs, they were so light and fluffy but full of flavor. The sipping sauce was on point too. For dinner I had the garlic pepper saut√©ed chicken - highly recommend! My wife had the pad thai and my son had the basil fried rice with chicken. These were also excellent choices. We will be back when we are in Seattle again and you should check it out as well.

Got the pad kra pow to go. The dish had potential but I feel like they were holding back. For example, I asked for a 4/5 in spice but what I got was closer to a 1/5 spice in my opinion. The savory flavors were mostly there but the low spice level meant that I couldn't get the pad kea pow experience I was expecting. Especially given the price, I was a bit disappointed.

Stopped here during the weekday with a colleague and it did not disappoint!

Service was quick and the waiter was friendly! I ordered the Pad Kra Pao with ground chicken and my colleague ordered the pineapple fried rice! Both were full of flavors, hot, delicious, and made to order!

It was also during the lunch hour, so we wanted it to be quick.

I highly recommend this location for Thai over other locations on the Ave!

Food was good but had small portions for the prices. Hard to compete with so many other Thai restaurants nearby, but the food came out quickly. I also wish they offered a spice tray on the side so you can add in your own heat level vs trusting that a 3 star is really a 3 star level of spiciness. It's a small restaurant with limited seating and may have a wait during peak times.
My partner and I saw this spot and decided to try them. Soooo good! We came during the calm times so it was super cozy and food was amazing.

editorial_summary.overview: Students prepare & serve locally sourced comfort fare at this cheery eatery for the UW community.

formatted_address: 1218 NE Campus Pkwy, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Cultivate

reviews.text:
If you have excess dining hall money, or want a higher quality meal, Cultivate is a great option! Also a fun place to go with friends.
I really enjoyed my food here both times. Bustling, upbeat environment with a order at the counter system. They also have long tables for groups to eat together! If getting french fries, I recommend getting their house made ranch as well.
They also have dessert options, I really liked the cheesecake.
Keep in mind prices are steeper than your average dining hall, but quality is much better. I personally wouldn‚Äôt order a steak here though.

Food is more expensive than nearby dining options, but is closer to restaurant-grade quality. Entrees are consistently good, and the dessert menu is a unique addition among West Campus dining halls.
Great atmosphere similar to an upscale diner, with clear views of both the kitchen and the street no matter which seat you choose. Very friendly staff. Water, napkins, and utensils are all self-serve from a table at the back. Water glasses are a bit too small, so I had to get up mid-meal frequently.

First off- i had the steak (medium rare), and it was great. came with a spicy herb sauce and golden potatoes on the side which were a solid 10/10 for me.
I also split two desserts with my friend: the tiramisu and the berry tart. the tiramisu was genuinely amazing, better than stuff i‚Äôve had elsewhere- 11/10. berry tart was good, but won‚Äôt be getting again unless i‚Äôm craving it in particular. tasted a lot like cherry cobbler. 8/10.

overall, i‚Äôm gonna go here more often. it‚Äôs the best dining experience i‚Äôve had with HFS and i‚Äôm sad it took me two years to finally come here.

This is a decent place for a campus dining. Their menu changes quarterly. The quality of the dish varies depends on who is cooking at that time. The service can be slow at a time. I like their burgers, fish and chips, and salad. I had chowder this time and it was good.
Street parking only.

Please don't get the steak. Just don't do that to yourself, you don't deserve it. I ordered a ribeye (28$ mind you) and asked for it to be done medium. When I received my food, it seemed as if they didn't listen as my "steak" was charred and over cooked, far past well done. The steak was dry and terribly difficult to consume and I'm surprised they even sell the product. But then again, it's an HFS "restraunt" so don't expect anything. Don't waste your time and money here, the ave offers better options at lower prices.

editorial_summary.overview: Buzzing, relaxed spot known for Vietnamese baguette sandwiches, plus pho, rice vermicelli & rolls.

formatted_address: 4142 Brooklyn Ave NE #105, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Saigon Deli

reviews.text: This was a solid bowl of pho! Great beef flavor, comes out piping hot. Noodles perfectly cooked and has a good amount of meat. Rice dishes also are really good! They are very friendly here; great prices, makes for a quick, casual place to eat pho.
It‚Äôs pretty good for the price, but the broth is INCREDIBLY oily. But if you‚Äôre just looking for a quick pho meal, you can go here

Pho w/ beef.
The broth leaned more on the savory side with a nice touch of oil leftover. The prices were the cheapest I‚Äôve seen compared to any other pho place but it only came with brisket slices. I did miss the tendons and tripe parts. Asked for extra thai basil and apparently I took the last one. The noodles were so clean I didn‚Äôt see any starch come from them when I broke it apart which is a great sign. Got the large size- large pho typically gouges me if I eat it all but I cleaned my bowl and didn‚Äôt feel gouges. It was the right amount but a tad smaller than expected but enough to satisfy after a 6 mi run

I think I‚Äôll be back to try their banh mi since the plate that they serve it on is a vibe and possibly the banh canh since it‚Äôs irregular

I got the vegetarian banh mi and it was anemic. Well - look at the photos. The tofu is tiny, soft, and dripping with oil. There's barely any veggie filling, there's no spicy mayo, and the bread was cold/ not toasted.

You can get much better on the Ave; I wouldn't come here again.
BEST Vietnamese food I have had recently. The broth has a great balance in taste, a definite good to if you are craving for soups

editorial_summary.overview: Quick-serve counter for sushi, teriyaki & other Japanese standards in a no-frills setting.

formatted_address: 4305 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Nasai Teriyaki

reviews.text: I love this place. Was my favorite place to eat in college. And now at 53 yrs old. Its still my favorite. LOVE IT.

This review is not necessarily holistic, I‚Äôll admit it. But if there‚Äôs one thing I can rely on when I‚Äôm in the depths of a horrible hangover or need a greasy reward, it‚Äôs the Nasai Teriyaki fried gyoza. Although I do feel that they are overpriced, they are consistently fried to absolute perfection. The outside is crunchy, while the inside is still juicy. The filling has a good flavor and is never dry, too squishy, or chewy. The pictures speak for themselves, just look at that golden color.

When I went the service was unreasonably slow. 6 gyoza took probably 15 minutes. I was in line, and it seemed that many customers had been waiting even longer for their food.

Again, I haven‚Äôt tried anything else and I don‚Äôt really plan on it‚Ä¶but I‚Äôd highly recommend trying the fried gyoza at least once.

Hole in the wall restaurant with plenty of seating and great food. You have to go around the hallway to order, it is a bit hidden when you first enter. When I went, I got gyoza and chicken teriyaki and had plenty of leftovers for another meal too.

Food was awesome üëå I ordered the chicken and beef teriyaki. It came with a salad I was only able to eat half because of the amount of food given. I ate the rest later on in the evening. Taste was extraordinary üòã

The service is superb - friendly, customer service and satisfaction oriented. The woman taking my order seems to know many in the local neighborhood and recognizes her ‚Äúregular customers.‚Äù She‚Äôs very kind and social.

Prices are fair.

Food is really delicious and cooked to order (hot foods are hot). Perfectly seasoned and balanced (not salty, not dry). Great options.

Thursday afternoon seemed to be a good time to find parking.

The interior dining area is cozy - not a lot of seating space, but convenient for a quick bite. Would definitely come back.

editorial_summary.overview: Mediterranean comfort foods feature at this small counter serve lined with tapestries.

formatted_address: 4222 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Sultan Gyros Grill

reviews.text: No over exaggeration, this was the BEST lamb gyro platter I‚Äôve ever had. And I‚Äôve been to Greece. The meat is fresh and hot, perfect portions, fantastic price, you can tell it is a family business which I love. I‚Äôm only in town for work, but if I‚Äôm ever back I would come here again without question!
Very friendly folks here at Sultan Gyro Grill! Great college eats, good shawarma, good veggie platter, excellent hummus. Just a straight forward lovely spot on the Ave.
I had the lamb shawarma, honestly not the best I had better, but if you are in the area and you are hungry works.

Sultan Gyros is amazing. They are always chill, friendly dudes, the food is fire, and the prices aren't terrible.

I wish I still lived down the street but weve made the 1hr+ drive a couple times. We have been trying to find a replacement but nothing compares.

At this point we have wasted so much money on mediocre greek/Arabic restaurants just to be disappointed! üòÇüòÇüòÇ

Maybe the Arabic Shawarma without onions would make it absolutely perfect, but overall, it‚Äôs amazing. I visit all the way from Everett just for this, and it‚Äôs totally worth it. A must-try spot, and I‚Äôll definitely be recommending it to friends!

editorial_summary.overview: This utilitarian take-out joint specializes in customizable burgers with a range of toppings.

name: A Burger Place

reviews.text: My favorite burger joint on the ave. Even with Just Burgers down the street. This is a great place for a cute date. Also the cleanest tables, always. Very clean and organized kitchen and space. Always peaceful. Neat little place to watch sports with friends too. A true staple.

Got a standard burger and fry

-quick service
-fries can improve, they weren't anything special

*burger was layered really well

Good affordable meal. Thanks!
The curly fries were amazing!!! Burgers were good too. Satisfied my burger craving, and the fries were an added bonus!

Been a fan of this place for several years now. It's a fun hole-in-the-wall place to stumble on. Great access if your riding on the Burke-Gilman Trail and want to stop of somewhere to eat. The food is high quality and well made with good service. The burgers are large and reasonably priced. They give a generous serving of fries.

Ordering is simple, it's a big checklist that you fill out. They have great toppings and are the only place I know that offers a halibut burger.
Their fries are very yummy and they're pretty quick too

editorial_summary.overview: Unassuming counter-serve eatery selling familiar Korean dishes for dine-in or takeout.

formatted_address: 4131 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: The BoB

reviews.text:
A great little Korean restaurant with amazing service and yummy food.

I had come here after looking for a spot to get some work done. After calling, the owners were very kind to let me know that they had WiFi available for paying customers. As this was surprisingly rare for other restaurants I called in for, I got myself some kimchi stew and set myself up at the table.

There is lots of seating available and you order at a self-serve kiosk near the entrance. The entrance is very accessible and they can host a variety of party sizes. Just make sure you let them know ahead of time if you are going to have a large group!

The stew had just the right flavors and came with kimichi and rice. For the price, I was very happy since I‚Äôd been eating lots of overpriced food since I landed here for my trip. They were quick with the meal prep, offered plenty of food for one, and offered wonderful customer service. They also have a bathroom that is accessible for paying customers! Couldn‚Äôt think of any place better to get some home cooked Korean dishes.

Had the military soup and it was soooo good on a chilly day. The portion size is generous and the white kimchi is nice and crunchy. The owners are so nice. I will be coming back to try the oxtail soup!

Came here for lunch and the kimchi bulgogi fried rice and dolsot bibimbap. Both were delicious (kimchi fried rice especially). We ate at the Korea Tofu House the night before (dolsot bibimbap, suhlung tang, ddukbokki with cheese) and I have to say, the food was clearly better here.  It can‚Äôt equal LA Korean food but it is still a solid offering. Food came out quick and service was kind.  Btw, I am Korean American and ate her with my teen daughter. We both enjoyed it.

I loved the spicy rice cakes. The sauce tasted so good and with the egg mixed in there, really good.
The kimchi noodle mix was my first time having a cold noodle dish and it was a great experience. There was a sweetness to the sauce and tanginess from the kimchi, the flavor balance between sweet and spicy was really something to appreciate. It was such a great experience. Thank you for such a unique flavor.
I would recommend this place to people and will be back!

Been twice now, once takeout and the other dining in. Both times the food has been delicious!! The bulgogi was perfectly cooked, all great pieces of meat, and so flavorful. The dumplings are tasty, especially the sauce. Kimchi fried rice with bulgogi was the right balance of kimchi flavor and bulgogi flavor, and proportion of rice to meat was good too. The service is fast and very friendly.

editorial_summary.overview: Charming, low-key eatery dispensing homestyle yakisoba, sushi, & stir-fry dishes plus take-out.

formatted_address: 4124 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: U DupBop Asian Fusion

reviews.text: Highly rated, for good reason! It's been a while since I've been to a place that feels like the food portion and quality are a great deal, but this place nails it. Large portions, fair price and wonderful flavors and quality ingredients. The place is quaint and the staff is friendly and fast. I would say this is the best General Tso chicken in town!

Solid meal. Delicious, filling, and affordable. I got the chicken teriyaki for $16.50 (excluding tip) and was very pleased with the portions. Friendly staff. Good mix of seating both indoors and on an outdoor patio. I will most certainly be coming back.

I was waiting on some car repairs and found this nice little place. The storefront was not right on the sidewalk. It seemed really clean compared to other restaurants nearby that I checked out. I got the sesame chicken (I think) and I loved it because it was still crispy after they had sauced it. Such a good meal at a nice price in a clean welcoming place. I highly recommend!

So good.  Jappanese, Korean, Chinese, they're doing it all.  Portions are big.  We went 2 days in a row despite there being 100 other restaurants nearby. Got a spicy teriyaki bento box one day, and General Tao the next.  Both were excellent.  All meals come with mixed greens and a nice vinagrette, and potstickers.  Just go, you wont regret it.

The area is small but most small places contain a massive amount of flavor.  The ambiance is astounding, the music is very pleasant, and the TV has great slides that articulate the cultural significance of the restaurant. Thank you for being a hidden gem of a restaurant.  They have limited staff so early in the morning but guaranteed flavor thank you.

formatted_address: 4106 Brooklyn Ave NE STE 101A, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Shake & Stack Burgers

reviews.text:
University of Washington  Hidden Gem
Located in University District of Seattle
and nestled in the college area, Stack and Shake is a true culinary treasure waiting to be discovered. From the moment you walk in, the staff makes you feel right at home ‚Äî their warmth and attentiveness elevate the entire dining experience.

For anyone searching for a local spot that deserves serious recognition, Stack and Shake is it. One visit, and you‚Äôll understand why this hidden gem has our full recommendation. üçîüçüü•§
Service was great parking was easy and free. The food was amazing. It was the best burger I ever had.

The food is great! Big portion and reasonable price, most importantly they are good. The fires are crispy and just the way i wanted :) The takeout was pretty fast, and the staff was friendly and polite, Im surprised with this kind of quality, would definitely go again!!

Winter is approaching, and if you need a warm meal this is the place!!! Beautiful restaurant well-kept and clean, the interior is breathable and welcoming all in all bringing the aesthetics of the store together making it complete. My new favorite burger spot!
I ordered the onion rings, Bacon cheeseburger, fries and drink only having to wait ~5 minutes for my meal. Cashier was very helpful, soft-spoken but held a fun conversation until my food arrived!
Burger was delicious and blows anything in its vicinity out of the water, no competition. They have a lovely in-house sauce but how many customization options. The portioning was fair and it still held up even when I ate it cold.
Overall I have to give it a 5/5 because I don't know what they can improve on! I have a lot of faith in the cook and can't wait to come back and try the whole menu.
Outstanding food and great service. This place is a must visit if you're a fan of burgers and shakes!

formatted_address: 4106 Brooklyn Ave NE suite 102 A, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Thai 2go (UW)

Curry noodle soup + Thai green tea

So buss

Very nostalgic and affordable for students. I ordered chicken pad Thai. The portions size and the amount of protein are reasonable.

Currently offering one free can of drinks with one dish. Not sure how long would the offer last.

Popcorn chicken supposed to be salty and spicy.  They made it taste so bad!!!  It tasted like they put a bunch of sugar in it. Love this place‚Äîfood is authentic and rice rolls are delicious. However, I ordered the pork and preserved egg rice rolls and they forgot the pork LOL. Would recommend double checking your takeout order before leaving‚Ä¶

Food portions are good, Pork belly is super tender, dumpling flavor excellent like the best brand at the store lol. I ordered the ‚Äúlees house special shrimp woton soup‚Äù and the ‚Äúbraised pork ribs rice roll‚Äù. The rice roll is pretty good, the rice roll skin is thin which is good. However, the pork ribs are a little over salty and the shrimp wonton is a little not what I expected.
General rating is a 4 out of 5.

formatted_address: 4129 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Yu Sushi & Katsu

reviews.text: Great food and staff! The staff are very nice and kind. Although there‚Äôs a small language barrier they always have a smile on their face and I feel welcomed. Remember to ask for water if you would like and hope you enjoy the dishes as much as I did.

I came into the restaurant and enjoyed the environment. Nice decor and quiet. We chose our seats and ordered through a QR code. This place is a self serve style restaurant.

The two critiques I have on this restaurant is the communication/ service and the food.

The food itself was good. We ordered the Katsu and sushi. Although, we weren't served any water for the period we were there.
We finished our food and went up to pay. We weren't checked on to see if anything was wrong. The only interactions were through our food being served and paying.

Now as we went to pay, gratuity was added on top of our meal. I  see this as a bit of confusion as to the only service was through bringing the food to us. after I go into pay, I sit down and the owner comes up. They questioned why we didn't tip and demanded a tip from us. They kept pushing for a tip until we did and left. Overall, I didn't hate the experience, but I think demanding tip after the service that was given to us is not fair. I want my interaction in a restaurant to feel like we are coming into a welcoming environment. I would be glad to tip if more service was provided, although, that just did not happen. If you come here for the food, great. If you come here for an experience, I recommend not.

Came for lunch with my sister. We ordered through a QR online, no water was served unless we ordered it; we would've had to pay for water - a but unsettling. Food came out things were good, food was good. The udon and katsu was good. She went to pay for our food... the cashier pressure her to pay a minimum of 10% tip. The total was already around $50 for 2 orders (tax included). His reasoning was because they do the dishes and it was "america style" to tip, also insulted her by asking if our parents didn't teach us to tip. Maybe his intention was not to insult her but it was rude to say so. Although the food was good, the service wasn't great.

This is a place where you pick a table, scan a QR code, order on your phone, then pay at the counter before you leave.

I got the curry pork katsu, I was happy with the food, but the service leaves a lot to be desired. My order came with a small soup and salad. I was not given any water, all the waiter did was come to my table twice to drop off food.

When I went to check out, there was a gratuity added to the total, and I'd went there solo, I was handed a receipt to sign and add another tip to, I didn't tip on top of the added gratuity. I'd heard someone else arguing about a tip while I was eating and I can see why. I was not offered a receipt.

While the food was fine, I wouldn't go back. If this is the level of service you have, you should just become a counter service place.
The pork cutlet was really good. Crispy, juicy, and well balanced. The service was great too, very friendly and attentive. Would definitely come back.

formatted_address: 4135 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Aladdin CharBurger

Highly recommend for any burger enthusiast!

Whenever i need a tasty, constant burger... this is the place.  A year may has passed but I always get greeted with a huge smile. The customer service is amazing, food is consistent and always great!

Love this place, food and staff! Go here, you will not be disappointed!

I like to come to this restaurant, the food is very tasty and all the condiments are very fresh

formatted_address: 4141 University Wy NE, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: IJ Sushi Burrito - UW

reviews.text:
This was my first time trying a sushi burrito and it was delightful! The interior was vast, and the service was quick and easy with a reasonable price. It is a nice place to chill with friends or to study when taking a break between classes.

The menu is very fresh, offering a wide range of vegetables and meats. I did not have any issues with the freshness of the vegetables, and the area was very clean, which I appreciated. The menu items are quite standard for most sushi places, offering things like California or tuna rolls. There are only a few options for vegetarians, such as the Vegan Roll. However, the place offers customization and unlimited toppings, which is very welcoming.

I would definitely recommend the customization option so you can find what is right for you. I wish I had tried the customization myself, but the Vegan Roll was not bad either.

I got mine with the spicy mayo and it was a surprise! The spice balanced well with the raw vegetables, and each bite got better and better. One thing I wished for was a seasoning option. Having plain salt, pepper, sesame, pickled ginger, or wasabi would be nice. I enjoy flavorful food, so I was a bit bummed that there was no extra seasoning. I had to rely on the mayo and seaweed for flavor instead. This is probably just a personal preference since I enjoy seasoning so much. However, everything else was good. The menu is straightforward, and the place is fast and clean.

Loved the huge sushi style burrito.

It tastes like a poke bowl inside nori and is super fresh and satisfying.

You can build your own burrito with many toppings.

I'm pretty happy with the place and get lunch here often.

Food - you can stuff it however you want which means it's filling and healthy. The ingredients taste fresh and the rice they use is well seasoned, which means the food is delicious.

Value - I feel like it's well priced. I'm a fairly big guy and I feel pretty full after eating it.

Other- the dude running the place is chill and polite, the restaurant is very clean, and I'm in and out in like 3-4 minutes.

I cannot recommend this place enough. :D

Great meal! Definitely a staple of mine in the area. Delicious food, clean space, friendly staff. Expect to pay ~$15-20 total, but know you get unlimited toppings!
- Spicy tuna and spicy mayo was a good combo

We've come here many times over the past 2 years and love the food everytime! Service depends on who is there/currently employed. For the most part the servers are helpful, friendly, and personable. Overall the experience is amazing, the place is clean and quiet (unless it's an active evening or weekend), and the board games ROCK.

editorial_summary.overview: Many flavors of self-serve bubble teas, plus snacks, offered in contemporary quarters with booths.

formatted_address: 4141 University Wy NE # 103, Seattle, WA 98105, USA
name: Boba Up

this place is great! the self-serve aspect is really fun, the pudding toppings were tasty, and the tea options were many. i‚Äôll definitely be back!

Cool concept! You literally just tell them what size of drink you want, they give you a cup and then you lit it rip! It‚Äôs a self-serve boba tea lounge. They let you sample plenty of milks/teas and all of them were really good! We grabbed the Ube milk tea with Egg. Very solid drink.

reviews.text:
I visited this poke place recently, hoping to grab a quick, fresh meal. Unfortunately, my experience left a lot to be desired.

Let‚Äôs start with the positive: the staff was friendly and efficient. They greeted me as soon as I walked in and were happy to answer any questions I had. Even as the line started to build up, they kept things moving smoothly, which I appreciated. Service was definitely a bright spot in an otherwise lackluster visit.

However, the quality of the food was a major letdown. The fish in my poke bowl didn‚Äôt taste fresh at all. The texture was off, and there was an unpleasant odor that made it hard to enjoy the meal. Freshness is key for a place that serves poke, and unfortunately, this was far from what I expected. I couldn‚Äôt even finish the bowl because the fish just didn‚Äôt sit right.

The cleanliness of the space was another issue. The restaurant itself felt a bit neglected‚Äîsticky counters, tables that hadn‚Äôt been wiped down, and a general sense that the place could use a serious cleaning. It wasn‚Äôt what I expected from a restaurant that specializes in raw fish, where hygiene is a top priority.

While the service was definitely up to par, the food quality and the cleanliness of the space need major improvements. I was really hoping for a better experience, especially considering how convenient the location is. But given this visit, I won‚Äôt be coming back again.

I recently dined at Poke Bay and was thoroughly impressed by the freshness of their seafood. The fish in my poke bowl tasted like it was caught that very morning‚Äîfirm, succulent, and full of flavor. Every bite was a testament to their commitment to quality. The variety on the menu was equally impressive, with an array of toppings and sauces that allowed me to customize my bowl to my exact liking. It's refreshing to see such a wide selection of fresh vegetables and unique mix-ins that go beyond the typical offerings. The staff's recommendations were spot-on, guiding me to create a bowl that was both nutritious and indulgent. The generous portions left me feeling satisfied without being heavy, and the vibrant, crisp ingredients made the meal an absolute delight. Poke Bay has certainly set the bar high for poke in the city!

I'm from Hawaii, so I'm always on the lookout for the next new poke spot. Poke Bay just opened on the Ave (right in front of Boba Gem and across from Jai Thai) and they were having a 20% off sale for their grand opening, so I popped in to give them a try!

TL;DR: It's not authentic Hawaiian-style poke. However, it's a decent American-style poke bowl (where the poke isn't pre-mixed beforehand and the toppings greatly outweigh the amount of fish). I'd come back solely for the unusual fact that they have crawfish and shrimp tempura in their standard protein options.

The interior is bright, clean, and minimalist -- just a bar to order and some seating. One individual bathroom. Note that there is VERY LIMITED seating: 1 table for four people, 1 table for two people, and 5 counter seats. When I came in, they were playing a mix of alternative and Disney music at medium volume.

In terms of food, it was pretty standard Seattle poke-bowl fare and pricing. Choose a "signature bowl" with pre-set ingredients (Regular $13.99 and Large $16.99) or build your own bowl (Regular $13.99 for 2 proteins, Large $16.99 for 3 proteins, +$3 for an extra scoop of protein). They had drinks to purchase but I didn't see a free water dispenser.

For folks unfamiliar with poke bowls, here's how to build your own bowl:
1. Walk to the far right edge of the counter, and tell them what size you want.
2. Choose a base (rices and salad), 2-3 scoops of protein (variety of cubed fishes, shrimp tempura, crawfish, or tofu).
3. Add an unlimited number of sides (vegetables, crab salad, edamame, ginger, etc).
4. Choose your sauce (I'm unclear if there's an extra charge for multiple sauces or not).
5. Add an unlimited number of toppings (crispy onion, jalape√±os, tempura flakes, etc).

Enjoy!

I didn‚Äôt like the house shoyu either, the rice was clumping, and the toppings weren‚Äôt fresh (lots of browning) or very appetizing. It doesn‚Äôt compare at all to the other nearby poke places. I‚Äôve celebrated birthdays, recovered from injuries, and unwound after long weeks with these pies, and more than once this stores pizza and bread bites have turned a rough day into a great night.

I know this sounds dramatic for a chain pizza place, but this store really nails both food and hospitality. Friendly faces at the counter and a team that clearly cares about what they‚Äôre making. My family has been eating Domino‚Äôs for generations- my grandfather, my dad, me- and I‚Äôve tried a lot of pies over the years. This location is easily the best I‚Äôve ever had, and is likely a big driver to why my kids when I have them will grow to loving Domino's as well.

reviews.text:
If you‚Äôre looking for an honest review, here it is.

I‚Äôve been coming to this place for about 4 years now, and without a doubt, it‚Äôs the best. The flavor is incredible, and you can truly tell the food is made with love, effort, and dedication.

From the very first day I discovered teriyaki‚Äîwhether chicken, beef, or ribs‚ÄîI tried many different places. Some were honestly a 2/10. But when my friends invited me to try this teriyaki spot, everything changed. Even after all these years, I never get tired of coming back. I‚Äôve had a long food journey, and over time I‚Äôve realized many things about this particular place.

1. Homemade, delicious food
If you‚Äôre looking for comforting, homemade-style food where almost any dish will be delicious, this is the place. Based on my experience over these 4 years, my top recommendations are: ribs, beef, chicken, rice, takoyaki, egg rolls, miso soup, and shrimp or vegetable tempura. Every single one is consistently amazing.

2. A place made with heart
Over the years, I‚Äôve noticed that this restaurant is truly one of the few places that is genuinely made with effort, dedication, care, and love. The owner is a kind and sweet person. If it‚Äôs your first time, you might feel a bit unsure because English isn‚Äôt his first language‚Äîbut once you understand that, you‚Äôll see how hard he tries to communicate and make sure you‚Äôre taken care of.

If you‚Äôre a kind and patient person, you‚Äôll immediately understand that he‚Äôs simply someone working hard to move forward and break the language barrier. I‚Äôve known him for 4 years now, and even though we don‚Äôt exchange many words, it‚Äôs very clear that he‚Äôs incredibly kind, caring, and genuine‚Äîjust a bit introverted.

3. An unforgettable family experience
I also brought my family here while they were visiting on vacation, and everyone was able to enjoy this delicious food. My brother and my dad are extremely open to trying food from different cultures, especially Asian cuisine. My brother, who has tried countless restaurants‚Äîeven in other countries‚Äîhad never tasted rice with such an incredible flavor. He enjoyed it so much that he ended up eating four plates of rice because he absolutely loved it.

They were also amazed by the flavor of every dish we tried, including the takoyaki, egg rolls, and most of the menu. That time, we ordered one of almost everything so we could try the variety, and everyone was completely impressed. That was two years ago, and to this day, every time we try a new restaurant, they still mention this place and say that without a doubt, the food here is unforgettable and incredibly delicious.

This place isn‚Äôt just about good food; it‚Äôs about heart. I will continue coming back without a doubt.

Absolute gem. Had a delicious chicken curry katsu that took me straight back to Japan. The curry was flavorful with tender veggies, the chicken crispy and juicy, and the rice was perfectly cooked and almost sticky.

It even came with a side salad or miso soup, and all for a very reasonable price! Hard to find any food around Seattle that matches this quality and quantity.

The service was very brief and of few words, which as someone who has been to Japan I can appreciate. The chef / owner came out of the kitchen as I was leaving to thank / say goodbye, which is awesome and reminded me of restaurants in Japan.

Surprisingly, I was the only person in for lunch at the time. I think more people should try this place.

I‚Äôve dined in twice now and oh my god. SO GOOD. I‚Äôm super picky with my food and unfortunately get full very easily and wow. Wow. Wow. I ate everything. Giant plate of beef fried rice for $13 AND comes with some of the best miso soup I‚Äôve ever had. Shared with my S/O and filled us up. Everything is hand made down to the onions in the soup and made fresh. If you‚Äôre genuinely looking for a place to check out TRY THIS. They only have one person doing it all and we should give him some love. Genuinely so good guys.

No greetings, no small talk and no thank you at the end of my meal. The food was alright. The chicken teriyaki was good, but the beef was a little dry. The salad was very small and so was the miso soup that came along with my teriyaki meal. Very lack luster experience for being the only customer in the entire place.

reviews.text: I got the kimchi Korean Street Toast and the Tuna Kimbap and it was so delicious! The street toast wasn‚Äôt spicy at all, but it balanced the sweetness. I was amazed the portion size of the ingredients and the customer service was fantastic. I‚Äôll definitely be coming back to try their other dishes.

You don‚Äôt want to miss this gem! As a Korean who frequently visits Seoul, I can say the food here is better than most spots in Seoul and is very authentic. I spoke to the owner briefly and learned that they use high quality ingredients and the recipe is thoughtfully crafted by their family based on what they enjoy at home. It‚Äôs a very clean and inviting space, perfect for a meal with friends or a casual date spot!

There‚Äôs a pretty good selection of Korean favorites here - tteokboki, mandu, assorted jeon, and even mul naengmyeon! But I think 9/10 times I come here I‚Äôm probably getting the toast (Korean style sandwich). No hate to those other things, and while we have had plenty of kbbq and soondubu places in the U-District, this is the only place making the legit toast like in SK.

The sandwich comes like a tower - impossibly tall, with a huge cabbage and egg patty in the center that‚Äôs covered in cheese, ketchup and mustard. The sandwich comes with a knife and fork on the side, almost like they anticipate most humans cannot unhinge their jaw like a python to take a bite of that thing.

Theres a trend of modern Korean food to add a lot of sweetness to savory dishes to create that sweet-salty flavor (‚ÄúÎã®Ïß†Îã®Ïß†‚Äú), I appreciate they hold back some of the sweetness here. There are some versions of this toast that literally coat one slice in sugar like a pastry, and while people love it, it takes some getting used to. So props to them for understanding the American palate here, there is a little sweetness in the sandwich, mostly from the ketchup, but balanced and not at all overwhelming.

Last note - my friend got tteokguk and when I tried her broth I could really taste the dashi stock - it‚Äôs obvious it‚Äôs been legit made with kelp and anchovy. No corners cut.

Also, service was good and everyone there is really nice.

editorial_summary.overview: Stylish quarters in a casual art deco style hotel offering a rooftop bar, a cozy lounge & a gym.

reviews.text: What a fun gem of a place in U District. Comfortable, clean, spacious, funky decor, a great coffee shop in the lobby, and a rooftop bar and restaurant with terrific views. Super friendly service - shoutout to Luke at the front desk- and overall a great experience. My only constructive criticism is when you only have two elevators, fixing the broken one has to be top on the priority list. :-)

The rooms are very small but cute and updated. Outside noise is okay--not terrible but not quiet, either.

My complaint is that upon checking in I received no information about the amenities such as where the restaurants are, where the ice machines are located (the even floors--found this out by calling the front desk), and how to use the supposed 15 dollars a day we are supposed to get for staying here--never did learn how to use this).

Upon checking in I was handed a card in an envelope with my room number but not told what floor I was on--I guessed and was right. I was also not told (and no signage) that one has to press the room key to a black plastic beveled box on the wall to get the elevator to input my room number. Again, maybe just basic information that could have been communicated either with the front desk or with signage in the elevator.

The room itself has zero information about the hotel--no printed docs or even a QR code to scan to learn more. I had to call the front desk to learn where the exercise room is--Mezzanine level  (which the front desk clerk then condescendingly explained to me as I suppose someone over 50 must not understand). I had no idea about the restaurants in the hotel--where they are located, hours, or menu--no information at check-in and no information in the room). The check-in was okay, but I definitely received the vibe of "I couldn't care less about you or your stay.: I'm over 50 and female, but I dress well, shower daily, of sound mind and body, and articulate. I present as a normal professional adult.  Not sure why I deserved so little information or consideration.

No fridge or microwave in the room were negatives.  A fridge can be requested, but we arrived at 10pm and staff were not available to bring a fridge.  My milk got warm.  Hotel also ran out of regular coffee packets.  I called asking for regular coffee and was delivered extra decaf.  Asked at the front desk and they got me a comped coffee from the cafe, but I really just want something for when I wake up tomorrow.  I guess I'll run to 7-11 and get some instant.  These are not fatal flaws, the room was clean and quiet.

I cannot stress this enough. Read the reviews. My husband did not, and we instantly regretted it. Whoever is taking the photos for this hotel website. ü§£ They did an excellent job at making it look like something it's not. This hotel is old, outdated, and in a sketch neighborhood. Our room looked nothing like the photos, and it smelled old and musty. For charging upwards of $400 a night, this place i not worth it. There are no fridges or microwaves in the rooms. But if you ask the front desk, they will bring you a mini fridge. Jolene was an excellent help with that. The restaurant and rooftop terrace that they advertise are less than up to par. I really don't recommend this place. Even for one night

reviews.text:
